  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The chromosome-level genome assembly of chub mackerel (Scomber japonicus) represents a significant contribution to marine genomics, facilitated by a collaboration among prestigious institutions, including the National Institutes of Health and Seoul National University. Funded by prominent agencies like the National Research Foundation of Korea, this dataset has already seen downstream reuse, indicating its importance in the field.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The recent chromosome-level genome assembly of chub mackerel (Scomber japonicus), published in Scientific Data, highlights a rigorous scientific endeavor backed by a network of key institutions. Collaborators from the National Institutes of Health, Seoul National University, and Rockefeller University played pivotal roles in the project, illustrating a strong academic coalition driving forward marine research. The support from major funding agencies, including the National Research Foundation of Korea and the Howard Hughes Medical Institute, underscores the investment in this research area and its potential implications for marine biology and fisheries science.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">This dataset, hosted on a GitHub repository, provides a foundational resource that enhances data accessibility and transparency in the field. Its formulation not only presents the genomic sequences but also lays the groundwork for future studies on the evolutionary trajectories of marine species, showcasing the cooperative scientific spirit amidst leading edges of genomic research. Scholars have begun to cite this dataset within their works, reinforcing its relevance and the active interest it has sparked among researchers in related disciplines.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The impact of this assembly is evident in its demonstrated downstream reuse, with proven evidence of four instances where the data has been utilized to advance other research projects. This reuse is a clear indicator of the dataset's value in fostering further investigations into the adaptive mechanisms of marine organisms. Additionally, the dataset is expected to support broader inquiries into the ecology and conservation of fish species, enriching the scientific community's toolkit for studying oceanic ecosystems.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">With three citations from various venues, including Fish & Shellfish Immunology and Developmental & Comparative Immunology, this work is beginning to permeate academic discourse around marine genetics. The contributions of the project also reflect geographical insights, with a notable citing landscape primarily from South Korea, Japan, and China, showcasing the regional interest and collaboration in marine biogenomics. Overall, the assembly of the chub mackerel genome presents a significant milestone for both the scientific community and aquatic biodiversity research.</p>",
